<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Most rosé wines are crafted for immediate enjoyment, but understanding their aging potential helps maximize your cellar investment. <strong>Premium rosés from renowned producers like Domaine Tempier Bandol or Château d'Esclans Garrus</strong> can develop beautifully over 5-8 years, while everyday Provence rosés peak within 1-2 years of vintage.</p>

<h3>Peak Drinking Windows by Style</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Light Provence rosés:</strong> Drink within 18 months for optimal freshness</li>
<li><strong>Structured Bandol rosés:</strong> 3-7 years, developing savory complexity</li>
<li><strong>Champagne rosé:</strong> 5-10 years for vintage bottlings</li>
<li><strong>Rhône rosés:</strong> 2-4 years, balancing fruit and earthiness</li>
</ul>

<h3>Evolution Over Time</h3>
<p>As rosé ages, the vibrant red fruit flavors of strawberry and cherry gradually shift toward <strong>dried fruit, orange peel, and honey notes</strong>. The wine's beautiful salmon-pink hue deepens to amber-copper tones. Unlike red wines, rosés contain minimal tannins, so aging relies on acidity structure and phenolic compounds extracted during brief skin contact.</p>

<h3>Proper Storage Requirements</h3>
<p>Store rosé at <strong>55°F (13°C) with 70% humidity</strong> in a dark environment. Keep bottles horizontal to maintain cork moisture. Rosé's delicate color compounds are particularly sensitive to UV light, making proper storage crucial for preventing premature browning.</p>

<h3>Recognizing Proper Aging vs. Spoilage</h3>
<p>Well-aged rosé develops <strong>tertiary aromas of dried herbs, almonds, and subtle spice</strong> while maintaining clean, focused flavors. Warning signs include excessive browning (beyond natural deepening), oxidized sherry-like aromas, or loss of all fruit character. The wine should retain bright acidity even as it evolves—if it tastes flat or overly soft, it's past its prime.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between Provence rosé and Spanish rosado?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Provence rosé typically showcases delicate pale salmon colors with crisp minerality, subtle red fruit, and herbal notes from Grenache, Cinsault, and Syrah grapes grown in limestone soils. Spanish rosado tends to be deeper in color with more pronounced strawberry and cherry flavors, often made from Tempranillo or Garnacha with slightly higher alcohol levels and more fruit-forward character.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should rosé wine be served ice-cold like white wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Rosé should be served chilled at 45-50°F (7-10°C), which is slightly warmer than most white wines but cooler than reds. Serving too cold (below 40°F) will mute the delicate fruit flavors and aromatics that make rosé special. Remove the bottle from the refrigerator about 10-15 minutes before serving to reach the optimal temperature.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long can you keep an opened bottle of rosé wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">An opened bottle of rosé will maintain its best quality for 3-5 days when refrigerated with a proper wine stopper or vacuum seal. The higher acidity in most rosés helps preserve freshness longer than many red wines, but the delicate fruit character will begin to fade after the third day. Light, crisp styles like Provence rosé are more fragile than fuller-bodied rosés from warmer climates.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibeld text-wine-700 mb-2">Is rosé wine a good choice for wine beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Rosé is excellent for beginners because it bridges the gap between white and red wines with approachable fruit flavors, moderate acidity, and typically lower tannins. The food-friendly nature and refreshing character make it less intimidating than complex reds, while offering more body and interest than basic white wines. Start with dry styles from Provence or Loire Valley to develop your palate.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the biggest mistakes people make when buying rosé?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is assuming all rosés are sweet – many quality rosés are bone dry with just 1-2 grams of residual sugar. Another error is buying rosé that's more than two years old, as most are meant to be consumed young and fresh. Avoid rosés that are dark pink or orange-tinged, which often indicates over-extraction or oxidation.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are expensive rosé wines worth the premium price?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Premium rosés ($20-40+) from renowned regions like Bandol, Tavel, or top Provence estates offer greater complexity, better vineyard sites, and more careful winemaking than budget options. However, excellent value rosés exist in the $12-18 range from regions like Languedoc, Portugal's Vinho Verde, or Washington State. The key is understanding the producer's reputation and the wine's intended style rather than just price.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wine alternatives work well if you enjoy dry rosé?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">If you love dry rosé, try light-bodied reds served chilled like Beaujolais, Pinot Noir from cool climates, or Italian Dolcetto. Crisp white wines with good texture such as Sancerre, Albariño, or unoaked Chardonnay from Chablis offer similar refreshing qualities. Orange wines (skin-contact whites) also provide the complexity and slight tannin structure that rosé drinkers often appreciate.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do you identify high-quality rosé by looking at the bottle?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look for pale to medium pink color (avoid dark or orange hues), clear glass bottles that protect the wine from UV damage, and recent vintage dates (current or previous year). Quality indicators include specific vineyard designations, traditional wine regions like Provence AOC or Tavel, and producer names with established reputations. Avoid rosés in dark bottles, which may hide color defects or oxidation.</p>
